Here is some more leisurely reading from the same artical:<br><br>
Many of those persistent stereotypes are rooted in the caricatures created by the pro-North Vietnam movement, as distinguished from Americans who genuinely opposed the war because of its divisive effect on the nation.<br>
In 1995, during a taping of CNN's Crossfire, even 1972 presidential candidate George McGovern admitted to Vietnam vet author Jim Webb: &quot;What you don't understand is that I didn't want us [America] to win that war.&quot;<br>
James Fallows, editor of U.S. News &amp; World Report, said of his fellow Harvard classmates: &quot;If you wanted to actively exult at a victory of the Viet Cong, then you were a progressive.' What that entailed was chanting &quot;Ho Ho Ho Chi Minh, the NLF is going to win,&quot; waving the NVA banner and defiling the American flag.<br>
Indeed, during the 1969-70 academic year, 1,800 demonstrations, 200 deliberate fires and eight deaths occurred on campuses.  Yet when the Building and Trades Council of Greater New York mobilized 100,000 workers to &quot;support our boys in Vietnam:' they were universally condemned by the press as &quot;hardhat rioters&quot; who hurt innocent protestors.<br>
Army nurse Lynda Van Devanter wrote her parents in 1969: &quot;It hurt so much sometimes to see the paper full of demonstrations, especially people burning the flag.  Fight fire with fire, we ask here.  Display the flag, mom and dad, please, every day.  And tell your friends to do the same.  It means so much to us to know we're supported, to know not everyone feels we're making a mistake being here.&quot;<br>
Vietnam veteran William K. Lane, Jr., wrote in the Wall Street Journal in 1988 how he &quot;recalled the curses, the hatred we felt when the New York Times clips arrived claiming the South Vietnamese and American victory in the Tet Offensive was actually a defeat.'<br>
Reviling soldiers and non-repentant veterans was all part of the tactics.  And yet for 25 years, those who participated in these activities deny it ever happened.  Accounts are innumerable.  Author Bob Greene did such a good job of chronicling them in Homecoming that a reviewer was compelled to ask: &quot;How many acts of desecration can you read about without your stomach twisting into tight knots?&quot;<br>
B.T. Collins, who lost an arm and a leg in Vietnam, was an early returnee in 1967.  He said he could forget the &quot;undisguised loathing&quot; of coeds in Manhattan, but not the rest.  He recounted in Reader's Digest.-<br>
 &quot;What hurt more was the embarrassed silence of the majority, who stood by and let it happen, who turned away without acknowledging the sacrifices we had made in a long and terrible war.'<br>
Silence was hardly the problem on campuses for vets using the GI Bill.  Arthur Harbison started school in September 1969.  &quot;A huge North Vietnamese flag was waved in front of me at a college orientation session,&quot; he said.<br>
Vice President Al Gore, a Harvard graduate himself and hardly a hawk, recently recalled his return to his alma mater in Cambridge in September 1969 while home on leave.  His hair cut short and walking through the streets in uniform, he &quot;became so angry at the presumption of those who instantly shouted epithets and sneered.&quot;<br>
Tom Lickness said, &quot;Returning home brought another, disappointing lesson.  We were, it seemed, not welcome.  In college, a fellow student told me she did not date Vietnam War veterans.'<br>
Ironically, relatively few of the men in Vietnam were enthusiastic war supporters, at least while they wem there.  &quot;Few of us felt any loyalty to this war,&quot; wrote Michael Clodfelter in his memoirs, The Pawns of Dishonor (1976).<br>
&quot;But we did possess a great loyalty and kinship to each other, to our reputations as individuals and as units.  We were like sons with little love left for our harsh and cruel mother, but fiercely determined to defend her name and honor against all slurs .... And so we reacted bitterly to the advocates of peace.&quot;<br>
This all went over the public's head.&quot;The most common experiences of rejection were not explicit acts of hostility&quot;, concluded Christian Appy in WorkingClass War, &quot;but quieter, sometimes more devastating forms of withdrawal, suspicion and indifference' &quot;<br>
This should not have come as any surprise.  After all, just look at the most indel ible images.  &quot;The public was left with one climactic image of their soldiers in Vietnam-losing the Tet Offensive while massacring civilians at My Lai,&quot; wrote the trio of authors of The Vietnam Veteran.<br>
Then you had self-professed anti-war activist psychiatrists-who were supposed to be counseling Vietnam vetsclaiming this nonsense: &quot;My Lai epitomizes the Vietnam War ... because every returning soldier can tell of a similar incident, if on a somewhat smaller scale.'<br>
A small minority of veterans took the cue from this line, accepting the role of victim and seeking approval from the media.  They became the darlings of the press-portrayed as the spokesmen for all vets when in fact they were atypical.<br>
Marine vet Phil Caputo and author of A Rumor of War, had this to say: &quot;The men who fought in Vietnam are being looked upon as victims, often by the very sort of people who reviled them-liberal columnists, actors and actresses, academics, the usual crowd who need some oppressed group to pity and champion.<br>
&quot;Unfortunately, some veterans are falling into this sentimental trap, having been denied the laurels due victorious heroes, they are clutching at the sprigs of sympa thy offered the victim.  Most veterans, though, reject this course.'<br>
Lickness, an infantry platoon leader with the Ist Airborne Division in 1968, no doubt spoke for vets who take pride in their service when he wrote a 1996 Veterans Day essay for the Wall Street Journal: &quot;We did not know we were losing the war to those with names like Jane, Tom, Bill and Ramsey.  Our leaders in the field fought side by side with us.  We had not heard of male bonding, but survived because of esprit de corps.<br>
&quot;We trusted each other with our lives.  We needed to be alert, so we did not take drugs, saving our intemperance for beer in the rear area.  We learned about courage, determination, camaraderie, selflessness and appreciation for living.'<br><br>

